<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Annuity" title="Annuity">Annuity</a>.</div>
<p>The term <b>annuity</b> is used in <a href="/wiki/Finance_theory" title="Finance theory">finance theory</a> to refer to any terminating stream of fixed payments over a specified period of time. This usage is most commonly seen in discussions of finance, usually in connection with the valuation of the stream of payments, taking into account <a href="/wiki/Time_value_of_money" title="Time value of money">time value of money</a> concepts such as <a href="/wiki/Interest_rate" title="Interest rate">interest rate</a> and <a href="/wiki/Future_value" title="Future value">future value</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Examples of annuities are regular deposits to a savings account, monthly home mortgage payments and monthly insurance payments. Annuities are classified by payment dates. The payments (deposits) may be made weekly, monthly, quarterly, yearly, or at any other interval of time.</p>
